-- Japan, China, India, South Korea, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-13T22:25:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-13/japan-china-india-south-korea-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Bank of Japan will begin a two-day policy board meeting
that will end tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.125 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 88.69 per dollar at 7 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The government will sell 28 billion yuan ($4.1
billion) of one-year bonds today.  
 Economic growth slowed to 10.5 percent in the second
quarter from 11.9 percent in the previous three months,
according to the median estimate of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg before the data is released tomorrow. Consumer prices
climbed 3.3 percent in June from a year earlier, the most since
October 2008, a separate survey showed before data also due
tomorrow.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.55 percent. The yuan was at 6.7720 per dollar.  
 India: The wholesale price index rose 10.8 percent in June
from a year earlier, the most in three months, according to the
median estimate in a Bloomberg survey of economists before the
release of data today.  
 The government will sell 20 billion rupees ($426 million)
of 91-day bills and 10 billion rupees of 364-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.62
percent. The rupee was at 46.7825.  
 Malaysia: The government will sell 3 billion ringgit ($934
million) of five-year Islamic bonds today. The central bank will
sell 1 billion ringgit of 124-day Islamic notes and 1.5 billion
ringgit each of 91-day and 210-day notes today.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.43 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.2035.  
 Singapore: Gross domestic product expanded at an annualized
pace of 23 percent in the second quarter and increased 17.3
percent from a year earlier, based on the median estimates in
Bloomberg surveys of economists before data today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.37 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3754.  
 South Korea: The government will report the unemployment
rate for June today. It was 3.2 percent in April, the lowest
level since October 2008.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.52 percent. The won was at 1,212.30.  
 Thailand: The central bank will increase the benchmark
interest rate to 1.5 percent from 1.25 percent when policy
makers meet today to review monetary policy, according to 13 of
19 economists surveyed by Bloomberg. The rest forecast no
change.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent debt due in May 2015 was
3.10 percent. The baht was at 32.38.  
